[FEN "5rk1/R4pp1/p3p2p/1p6/8/P3P2P/1P3PP1/6K1 b - - 1 2"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2022.04.11"]
[UTCTime "22:49:14"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ The position is desperate as our a pawn is destined to fall. Can you keep the position level? }
2... Rc8! (2... Rd8! { Just as good. Play Rc8 instead for the solution. }) 3. Rxa6 Rc1+ (3... Rc2? $16 { Too early. After b4, all of white's pawns are defended. Can you improve on this idea? }) 4. Kh2 Rc2 $10 { Fantastic! One of white's pawns on the 7th rank will fall and the game remains equal. } *


[Event "Rooks | Infiltrate for activity!: Exercise 4: Creating pigs"]
[Date "1979"]
[White "Konstantin Lerner"]
[Black "Adrian Mikhalchishin"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteElo "2475"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackElo "2480"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rooks | Infiltrate for activity!"]
[ChapterName "Exercise 4: Creating pigs"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/U7tTRtdj/PTOUuoVo"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "3r3k/2Rb4/2p5/P1R4P/4P1p1/8/rP3PK1/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ A more difficult puzzle. We have three pawns for the piece, but our true advantage lies in the activity of our rooks. Can you create something tangible from this? }
1. Re5! Be8 { I hope you noticed that black's Re8?? failed to Rxe8+ Bxe8, Rc8 with a decisive pin and win of the bishop. } (1... Re8? 2. Rxe8+ Bxe8 3. Rc8 $18) 2. Ree7! Rxa5?? { Black tries to eliminate the pawns, but allows a devastating finish. What threat did he overlook? } 3. Rh7+! Kg8 4. Rcg7+ (4. Rhg7+? $18 { Repeating moves does not get you anywhere. }) 4... Kf8 5. h6! $18 { Beautifully done! With Rh8# essentially unstoppable, black resigned.
PRO TIP: Pigs on the 7th often need a helping hand in order to create a mating net. Once we play h6, there's no escaping our net! } { [%cal Gh7h8] } (5. Rh8+?? { Oh no your rook! } 5... Kxg7 $19) *


[Event "Rooks | Infiltrate for activity!: Connecting your rooks"]
[Date "2022.04.11"]
[White "NoseKnowsAll"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rooks | Infiltrate for activity!"]
[ChapterName "Connecting your rooks"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/U7tTRtdj/s9xBXP9n"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "1nrq1rk1/4bppp/p2p4/1p1Pp3/1N2P3/1P2BP2/P2Q2PP/2R2RK1 w - - 4 20"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2022.04.11"]
[UTCTime "22:49:14"]

{ In this position, both sides are doing well to stop their opponent's rook from infiltrating on the c file, but there's a crucial problem in black's position: black's rooks are not connected. } { [%cal Bc1c8,Bc8c1] }
20. Rxc8! (20. Kh1? { Don't give black time to keep challenging the open c file! } 20... Qd7 $14 { Now that black can recapture on c8 with a rook, black's position has improved somewhat. Sure, it remains ugly, but white will need to do a lot more work to make any tangible progress. }) 20... Qxc8 { The queen is the worst piece to control an open file because she is so easy to kick around. } 21. Rc1 { White regains control of the open file. } 21... Qb7 22. Qc2 $16 { White cements their control of the c file forever. Qc7 is coming next, with decisive penetration on the 7th rank.
PRO TIP: Once you have control of an open file, double on it in order to infiltrate to the 7th rank! } { [%cal Gc2c7] } (22. Kh1? { Don't give black time to challenge the open c file! } 22... Rc8 $14) *


[Event "Rooks | Infiltrate for activity!: Controlling the open file"]
[Date "2022.04.11"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rooks | Infiltrate for activity!"]
[ChapterName "Controlling the open file"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/U7tTRtdj/V9yuittx"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r1r2qk1/1p2bppp/p3pn2/3p4/3P1B2/1P1QPN1P/P4PP1/R1R3K1 b - - 0 2"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2022.04.11"]
[UTCTime "22:49:14"]

{ As we've seen before, any rook trade will leave the other player with control of the only open file. But black has a way to force the issue... } { [%cal Bc8c1,Bc1c8] }
2... Ba3! { An important move! Once we control the c1 intersection square, there's no way for white to keep control of the c file. } (2... Rxc1+? 3. Rxc1 $10 { Giving up control of the only open file gives us nothing. }) 3. Rxc8 (3. Rc2!? { Black's queen and rooks are connected, so there's no way for white to keep a rook on the c file. } 3... Rxc2 4. Qxc2 Rc8 5. Qe2 $17 { Transposes to the main line. }) (3. Rd1!? Qb4 $17 { Black will double with Rc3 and Rac8 next. The c file is firmly in black's control. } { [%cal Gc8c3,Ga8c8] }) 3... Rxc8 { Black has firm control of the c file. The next step is infiltration on the 7th rank. } 4. Qe2 { White has one active try to keep a rook off of c2 } 4... Rc6 5. Rd1 Qc8 { Black is doubled and ready to infiltrate. } 6. Rd2? { White desperately tries to stop Rc2. } (6. Ne1 $17 { This passive move just to stop Rc2 is possibly best. White's pieces have all been moving backwards. }) 6... Ne4! { But black will not be denied! White now loses control of c2 by force. } 7. Rd1 Rc2 8. Qf1 Rxf2 $19 { Black's active pieces begin munching on every pawn on the 2nd rank.
Control of an open file can often start you on a road to victory! } *


[Event "Rooks | Infiltrate for activity!: Exercise 5: Squeak out an advantage"]
[Date "2022.04.11"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rooks | Infiltrate for activity!"]
[ChapterName "Exercise 5: Squeak out an advantage"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/U7tTRtdj/1tl44a1N"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r1br2k1/1p3p1p/n1p3p1/p3q3/P1Q1P3/2N3P1/1P3PBP/3R1RK1 b - - 1 2"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2022.04.11"]
[UTCTime "22:49:14"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ At first glance, this might appear to be an even middlegame. but if you focus on controlling the d file, I'm sure you can figure out the correct sequence. }
2... Be6! (2... Bg4 { Also good, but only if you respond to f3 by transposing to the main line. } 3. f3 $17) (2... Rxd1? { You just gave up the d file! } 3. Rxd1 $10) 3. Qe2 { Developing with tempo is a good start, but what's the point of this move? } 3... Bb3! $17 { Exactly! Now white is forced to give up control over the only open file. You can next plan to infiltrate on the d file. } (3... Qc5!? { A reasonable move that threatens Bc4, but after Rxd1+ Rxd1, Rd1 both sides equally control the d file. } 4. Rxd8+ Rxd8 5. Rd1 $15) *


[Event "Rooks | Infiltrate for activity!: Exercise 6: Remove the defenders"]
[Date "2022.04.11"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rooks | Infiltrate for activity!"]
[ChapterName "Exercise 6: Remove the defenders"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/U7tTRtdj/8BGWy9Pu"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r5k1/pp4pp/2bppr2/2n2p1q/2P5/P2P1NP1/4PPBP/1R1Q1RK1 w Qq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2022.04.11"]
[UTCTime "22:49:14"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ A tricky position. Black is building up for a kingside attack, but white is already poised for queenside play. How can you ensure your play hits first? }
1. d4! Ne4 { In general, allowing this knight to sit on e4 is a dangerous idea, but there is a concrete follow-up that you had to see before playing your last move. } 2. d5 exd5 (2... Nc3? 3. Qd3 Nxb1 4. dxc6 $18 { [%csl Gb1] }) 3. cxd5 Bd7 (3... Nc3? 4. Qb3 $18) 4. Rxb7 $16 { Nice job! While it's clear that there is still work to do in order to defend against black's kingside assault, taking the b pawn and activating the rook was an important step to retain the advantage. } *


[Event "FIDE Grand Prix"]
[Site "Dubai UAE"]
[Date "2002.04.07"]
[Round "4.4"]
[White "Teimour Radjabov"]
[Black "Viswanathan Anand"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteElo "2599"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackElo "2757"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rooks | Infiltrate for activity!"]
[ChapterName "Infiltration on the 8th"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/U7tTRtdj/EPdzq6we"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "1q1r2k1/2r1bpp1/p3pn1p/8/p1PP4/3B1Q1R/5PPP/BR4K1 b - - 1 26"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Rooks also love to infiltrate on the 8th rank, although there are no pawns there. Doubling on the 8th rank instead leads to kingside attacks and checkmate threats.

Here's a spectacular example from previous World Champion, Viswanathan Anand. }
26... Rxc4!! { This tactical blow must have come as quite a shock to Radjabov. } 27. Rxb8 (27. Bxc4?? Qxb1+ $19) 27... Rc1+ 28. Bf1 Rxb8 { Anand has seen that Rbb1 is an unstoppable follow-up, hitting both bishops and threatening back-rank mate. } { [%cal Gb8b1] } 29. Bc3 Rbb1 { Anand's pigs arrive on the 8th! } 30. Qd3 { Radjabov has successfully defended the f1 bishop, but there's one more trick to the position. } { [%cal Bd3f1] } 30... a3! { The passed a pawn decides the game. } { [%cal Ga3a1] } 31. Qxa6 a2 32. g4 (32. Qxa2?? Rxf1#) 32... Rxf1+ 33. Qxf1 Ne4 34. Ba1 (34. Ba5 a1=Q $19) 34... Nd2 $19 { White resigned rather than allow Anand a new queen.
PRO TIP: If you're able to get pigs on the 8th, you should be aiming for an all-out attack on the king. } *


[Event "Rooks | Infiltrate for activity!: Preventing infiltration"]
[Date "2022.04.11"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rooks | Infiltrate for activity!"]
[ChapterName "Preventing infiltration"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/U7tTRtdj/p0g49H7G"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r2r4/1pq1bp1k/2p1bnpp/4p3/4P3/4BNNP/1PPRQPP1/3R2K1 b - - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2022.04.11"]
[UTCTime "22:49:14"]

{ We know how important controlling an open file is: with control of an open file, you can infiltrate with your rook. Here, however black should play an unintuitive move to keep the advantage. }
4... Rdb8! { Brilliant! Since every infiltration square on the d file is already under black's control, black can cede the d file to white and keep more pieces on the board for eventual queenside operations. } { [%csl Bd8,Bd7,Bd6,Bd5,Bd4][%cal Be6d5,Be6d7,Be7d6,Be7d8,Be5d4] } (4... Rxd2?! 5. Qxd2 Rd8 6. Qe2 Rxd1+ 7. Qxd1 Qd6 8. Qxd6 Bxd6 $10 { Black would have nothing more than equality after trading all the major pieces. }) 5. Nh2 b5 $15 { Black has a slight pull and can look to infiltrate themselves on a2. White's d file is irrelevant.
PRO TIP: Controlling an open file is only important if there's an infiltration square! } { [%cal Ga8a2] } *


[Event "Rooks | Infiltrate for activity!: Exercise 7: A swift regrouping"]
[Date "2022.04.11"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rooks | Infiltrate for activity!"]
[ChapterName "Exercise 7: A swift regrouping"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/U7tTRtdj/xu3AxPTN"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r4rk1/p1q2bpp/4pp2/3p4/2pPn3/2P1PN1P/PRQ1BPP1/1R4K1 b - - 1 5"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2022.04.11"]
[UTCTime "22:49:14"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ White has control of the only open file, but black's remaining pieces have a lot more potential than white's. }
5... Nd6! (5... Bg6?! { A good idea, but sadly this runs into Nh4 with tempo. } 6. Nh4 Bf7 $15) (5... Rab8? { After the mass exchange of rooks, the position is only equal because of a Bxc4 trick! } 6. Rxb8 Rxb8 7. Rxb8+ Qxb8 8. Bxc4 $10) (5... Rfb8? { After the mass exchange of rooks, the position is only equal because of a Bxc4 trick! } 6. Rxb8+ Rxb8 7. Rxb8+ Qxb8 8. Bxc4 $10) (5... Qa5? { A good try but there's a Bxc4 trick that keeps white in the game } 6. Bxc4 $10) 6. Re1 { Not only did this impressive retreating move cover all the entrance squares on the b file, but it came with the threat of Bg6 winning an exchange. } { [%cal Ba7b6,Bd6b5,Bd6b7] } 6... Bg6 (6... Rfb8!? $17 { Interesting try. Let's first control the b file forever by covering the b1 square. }) (6... Rab8!? $17 { Interesting try. Let's first control the b file forever by covering the b1 square. }) 7. Qc1 { White's pieces have all retreated to passivity. Can you now secure a stable advantage? } 7... Rfb8! $17 { Exactly! Once you control the b1 square, you are now able to steal the b file from white AND keep all of the advantages of the original position. } (7... Rab8! $17 { Just as good. Play Rfb8 instead for the solution. }) *


